Professor Adrian Puren from the National Institute of Communicable Diseases spoke with eNCA's Dan Moyane. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - South Africa is experiencing different COVID-19 patterns compared to the second wave. This according to Professor Adrian Puren from the National Institute for Communicable Diseases. READ: COVID-19 third wave hits Gauteng He said the Northern Cape, Free State and the North West are showing signs of either being in the third wave or close to it. On Friday, the Gauteng government confirmed the province has officially entered a third wave. READ: KZN ready and prepared for COVID-19 third wave: Zikalala "For all intents and purposes, the Free State was in the second wave, came out and went back straight into a third wave. Northern Cape as well, has gone into its third wave," Puren said. "Gauteng is pretty close to, if not in, its third wave. It was already declared by the province premier. "North West, when I look at the data, it's pretty close to the threshold so that will probably enter into the third wave," he said. While SA has not yet reached the new wave threshold for #COVID19, the current trajectory is concerning & if it remains on course we will enter a new wave in the coming weeks. Complying with preventative measures remain ever important.
